    detail: `Middle Ground Fallacy

Description:
In this question, the quoted claim is "Holly said that vaccinations caused autism in children, but her scientifically well-read friend Caleb said that this claim had been debunked and proven false. Their friend Alice offered a compromise that vaccinations must cause some autism, just not all autism.".
That is as if the shortcut alone were enough to prove the conclusion.

Example (question)
« Holly said that vaccinations caused autism in children, but her scientifically well-read friend Caleb said that this claim had been debunked and proven false. Their friend Alice offered a compromise that vaccinations must cause some autism, just not all autism. »

Example (everyday)
In a work meeting, someone says "Holly said that vaccinations caused autism in children, but her scientifically well-read friend Caleb said that this claim had been debunked and proven false. Their friend Alice offered a compromise that vaccinations must cause some autism, just not all autism." as if the shortcut alone were enough to prove the conclusion.

Example (another context)
In a policy debate, the same error shows up when people treat the claim as if the shortcut alone were enough to prove the conclusion.

How it works
The argument uses a shortcut instead of real evidence.
It sounds settled because the speaker is doing that as if the shortcut alone were enough to prove the conclusion.

So:
- The missing step stays hidden.
- A weak move can feel persuasive if nobody stops to inspect it.
- The conclusion sounds stronger than the evidence.

Key concept inside it
Middle Ground Fallacy:
Asserting that a compromise between two extremes must be the truth.

Why it matters
Explains why:
- It can make the real issue harder to see.
- It can make weak reasoning feel normal.
- It can hide the evidence the listener should be looking for.

The uncomfortable implication
A good-sounding shortcut can still leave the argument empty.
The argument can still fail even when it feels obvious.

One-line version
Middle Ground Fallacy = Asserting that a compromise between two extremes must be the truth.`,
