  604: {
    beginner: `Reification = Treating an abstract concept as if it were a real, concrete thing.`,
    detail: `Reification

Description:
In this question, the quoted claim is "Society demands this.".
That turns an abstract idea into something that sounds like a real person with wants.

Example (question)
« Society demands this. »

Example (everyday)
At a town hall meeting, someone says "Society demands this" as if society were a person standing in the room and issuing orders.

Example (another context)
In a budget debate, the same error shows up when people talk about "the economy" as if it could feel angry, want something, or speak for itself.

How it works
The argument gives an abstract idea human powers.
Once the concept sounds like an actor, it can seem more real and more forceful than it actually is.

So:
- The idea gets treated like a thing you can point to.
- The real people or institutions behind the issue disappear.
- The conclusion sounds concrete even though the subject is still abstract.

Key concept inside it
Reification:
Treating an abstract concept as if it were a real, concrete thing.

Why it matters
Explains why:
- It can make vague labels sound like hard facts.
- It can blur who is actually responsible for an outcome.
- It can turn a discussion about institutions into a fake discussion about a "thing."

The uncomfortable implication
An abstract noun can sound authoritative without explaining anything.
The argument can still fail even when it sounds polished.

One-line version
Reification = Treating an abstract concept as if it were a real, concrete thing.`,
  },
